ur]], [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.the-afc.com/competitions/fifa-world-cup/latest/news/groups-finalised-for-qatar-2022-china-2023-race |title=Asian Qualifiers draw to provide pathway to Qatar and China |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |work=The-AFC.com |date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n===Group A===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group A|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group B===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group B|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group C===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group C|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group D===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group D|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group E===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group E|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group F===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group F|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group G===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group G|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Group H===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Group H|show_matches=y}}\n\n===Ranking of runner-up teams===\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|transcludesection=Second place}}\n\n==Third round==<!--\n{{Main|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round}}-->\nThe third round consists of two groups of six teams. The first two teams in each group will qualify for the World Cup. The two third-placed teams proceed to the fourth round.<!--\n\n====Group A====\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|transcludesection=Group A|show_matches=y}}\n\n====Group B====\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round|transcludesection=Group B|show_matches=y}}-->\n\n==Fourth round==<!--\n{{Main|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Fourth Round}}-->\nThe two third-placed teams in each group from the third round will play against each other home-and-away over two legs to determine which team advances to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-offs]].<!--\n\nThe order of legs will be announced during the draw for the third round.\n{{:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Fourth Round}}-->\n\n==Inter-confederation play-offs==<!--\n{{main article|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC\u2013AFC play-off)}}-->\n\nThe [[#Inter-confederation play-offs|inter-confederation play-offs]] format is expected to be announced at a later date. Matches are scheduled to be played in March 2022.<ref name=\"fifacalendar\">{{cite web|title=INTERNATIONAL MATCH CALENDAR 2018\u20132024|url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/international-match-calendar-2018-2024.pdf?cloudid=p3ywicffz0zxeaomaajh|publisher=FIFA|date=April 2019|access-date=12 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105145356/https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/international-match-calendar-2018-2024.pdf?cloudid=p3ywicffz0zxeaomaajh|archive-date=5 January 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<!-- {{#lst:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|playoff1}} -->\n\n==Qualified teams==\nThe following teams from AFC qualified for the final tournament.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Team\n! Qualified as\n! Qualified on\n! data-sort-type=\"number\"|Previous [[National team appearances in the FIFA World Cup|appearances]] in [[FIFA World Cup]]<sup>'''[[#1|1]]'''</sup>\n|-\n| {{fb|QAT}} || {{sort|*|Hosts}} || {{dts|2 December 2010}} || 0 (debut)<!--\n|-\n| {{fb|}} || {{sort|A1|[[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round#Group A|Third Round Group A]] winners}} || {{dts|2021}} ||\n|-\n| {{fb|}} || {{sort|B1|[[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round#Group B|Third Round Group B]] winners}} || {{dts|2021}} ||\n|-\n| {{fb|}} || {{sort|A2|[[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round#Group A|Third Round Group A]] runners-up}} || {{dts|2021|addkey=1}} ||\n|-\n| {{fb|}} || {{sort|B2|[[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Third Round#Group B|Third Round Group B]] runners-up}} || {{dts|2021|addkey=2}} ||-->\n|}\n:<div id=\"1\"><sup>1</sup> '''Bold''' indicates champions for that year. ''Italic'' indicates hosts for that year.</div>\n\n==Top goalscorers==\n{{#invoke:Goalscorers|main|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|bold=yes|minimum=4}}<!--CAREFULLY update goalscorers at Module:Goalscorers/data/2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)-->\n\n==See also==\n*[[2023 AFC Asian Cup qualification]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/qatar2022/|Official FIFA World Cup website}}\n**[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/qatar2022/preliminaries/#asia Qualifiers \u2013 Asia], FIFA.com\n*[https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/fifa-world-cup/ FIFA World Cup], the-AFC.com\n\n{{2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers}}\n\n[[Category:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)| ]]\n[[Category:2022 FIFA World Cup qualification|Afc]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)]]\n[[Category:2019 in Asian football]]\n[[Category:2020 in Asian football]]\n[[Category:2021 in Asian football]]\n", "name_user": "JalenFolf", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification_(AFC)"}
{"title_page": "Ayyathan Gopalan", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian physician, writer, social reformer and philanthropist}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Fanpov|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = RaoSahib\n| name               = Ayyathan Gopalan\n| image              = Appan.jpg\n| caption            = Darsarji\n| other_names        = Darsarji\n| birth_name         = Ayyathan Gopalan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1861|03|03}}\n| birth_place        = Thalassery, Chettamkunnu (Pulappadi Illam)\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1948|05|02|1861|03|03}}\n| death_place        = Calicut Shanthi Ashram\n| resting_place      = Santhi Gardens (Ayathan family cemetry, Calicut)\n| movement           = Sugunavardhini movement\n| spouse             = {{marriage |Kallat Kausallyaammal|1878|1930}}\n| children           = 5\n{{endplainlist}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Madras Medical College]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Doctor|professor|social reformer}}\n| known_for          = Physician, Writing, Philanthropy, Social reform in Kerala\n| notable_works      = Bhramodarma malayalam (Bible of bhramosamaj)\n\nSaranjiniparinayam and Susheeladukham (Musical dramas)\n| mother             = Kallat Chiruthammal\n| father             = Ayyathan Chandhan\n| relatives          = \n| awards             = [[Rai Sahib]]\n}}\n{{Reformation in Kerala}}\n\n'''Rao Sahib Ayyathan Gopalan''', Social reformer of Kerala popularly known as '''Darsarji''', \"doctor\", a.k.a \"RaoSahib\", was an Indian physician, writer, social reformer and philanthropist. He is known mainly as the founder of the [[Sugunavardhini movement]], leader and propagandist of [[Brahmo Samaj]] in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|date=1884|publisher=[[Funk & Wagnalls]]|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> He denounced idol worship and fought to end those social practices he thought were unethical, but prevalent, in Kerala. Among his followers were [[Brahmananda Sivayogi]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmananda swami Sivayogy by A K Nair|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi by Pavanan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair \"Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku\"(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and His Selected Works by P.V. Gopalakrishnan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sreyas.in/brahmananda-sivayogi|title=sivayogi|website=|date=29 April 2013|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kerala Navothanam - Oru Marxist Veekshanam - P. Govindappilla (Chintha Publishers, Thiruvananthapuram-695001)|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and his selected works|last=Gopalakrishnan, P. V.|date=2002|publisher=Kalpaz Publications|isbn=8178351013|oclc=52726748}}</ref> [[Vagbhatananda|Vaghbatananda]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (1988), Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations |publisher=Mittal Publications|year=|isbn=9788170990949|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherdschalet.com, retrieved 19 March 2014|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". |journal=Social Scientist|volume=16|issue=9|pages=35\u201345|year=1988|url-status=live|doi=10.2307/3517171|jstor=3517171|last1=Kurup|first1=K. K. N.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vagbhatananda-admavidya.com/|title=Vagbhatananda|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mahar\u1e63i V\u0101gba\u1e6d\u0101nanda Gurud\u0113var.|last=Brahmavrathan, Swami.|date=1971|oclc=978079481}}</ref> and Brahmavadhi P. Kunhiraman. Gopalan honored Karat Govinda Menon (Sivayogi) as \"[[Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi|Brahmananda Swami]]\" for writing a collection of poems on the request of Brahmosamajists called \"Brahmasankeerthanam\" and also for extending his social services through [[Brahmo Samaj|Brahmosamaj.]] The formation of [[Sugunavardhini movement]], and Brahmosamaj played a significant role in the [[Kerala reformation movement]].\n\n==Biography==\nGopalan was born into the [[Ayathan School|Ayyathan]] family of Pulappadi Illam (Aristocratic Thiyya family of Malabar) in Chettamkunnu, [[Thalassery]], (formerly Telicherry), [[Kerala]]. He was the first son of Ayyathan Chandhan and Kallat Chiruthammal. His youngest sister, Ayyathan Janakiammal,<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Modern Kerala, Studies in social and agrarian relations (1988). Modern Kerala:Studies in social and agrarian relations|publisher=by K.K.N.Kurup. mittal publications 1988: K.K.N.Kurup.|year=1988|isbn=|location=|page=86}}</ref> was the first female doctor in Malabar, Kerala.\n\nHe attended [[Government Brennen College, Thalassery|Brennen School]] and [[Mission school|Mission High School]] and later joined [[Madras Medical College]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Annual Report of the Madras Medical College. Session 1855-56( -1876-77).|last=Madras Medical College.|date=1856\u201377|oclc=562478204}}</ref> on 19&nbsp;September 1884. He resisted immorality and superstition at an early age.  He was reluctant to follow any caste differences or customs.  During his college days, reading about the social renaissance movements in many countries he got attracted to [[Ram Mohan RoyRoy|Raja Ram Mohan Roy's]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nazir|first=Parwez|date=2011|title=Raja Ram Mohan Roy: Social Reform and Empowerment of Women|journal=Journal of Exclusion Studies|volume=1|issue=2|pages=1|doi=10.5958/j.2231-4547.1.2.013|issn=2231-4547}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sati, a writeup of Raja Ram Mohan Roy about burning of widows alive|last=Rammohun Roy, Raja, 1772?-1833.|date=1996|publisher=B.R. Pub. Corp|isbn=8170188989|oclc=38110572}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=1 January 2008|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Men I have seen; personal reminiscences of seven great Bengalis.|last=\u015a\u0101str\u012b, \u015aiban\u0101tha, 1847-1919.|date=1948|publisher=Sadharan Brahmo Samaj|oclc=11057931}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Killingley|first=Dermot|chapter=Rammohun Roy and the Bengal Renaissance|date=27 June 2019|pages=36\u201353|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198790839|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198790839.003.0003|title=The Oxford History of Hinduism: Modern Hinduism}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Reflections on the Bengal renaissance : [papers read at a seminar, \"Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance\"]|last=Seminar on Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance (1976 : Rajshahi University)|date=1977|publisher=Institute of Bangladesh Studies, Rajshahi University|oclc=557887410}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|chapter=Rabindranath Tagore: His Life and Thought|date=24 February 2016|pages=1\u201317|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315554709|doi=10.4324/9781315554709-1|title=The Philosophy of Rabindranath Tagore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> Brahmo Samaj. He joined Brahmo Samaj and engaged in its social activities.  Since then he was an active executive member of the General Committee of Calcutta Brahmo Samaj. He participated in the committee's annual conferences at various locations across India, along with Brahmo leaders such as [[Keshub Chandra Sen|Kesub Chandra Sen]], [[Debendranath Tagore]], Sivanath Sastri, [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[R. G. Bhandarkar]], and others. In 1888, he obtained a medical degree with honors and entered into [[Public service|government service]]. After that, he worked as a [[medic]] in several hospitals across South India and as a medical lecturer. He also served as a magistrate during the [[British rule]] in Malabar.\n\nGopalan married Kallat Kausallyaammal on 30&nbsp;December 1894. According to the rituals involved, this was the first Brahmo wedding. Ramakrishna Gobal Bhandhakar, a Brahmo leader and social reformer at that time, conducted the wedding at the Madras Brahmo Samaj. Several Brahmo leaders presided over the wedding. Kallat Kausallyaammal was a supporter of Gopalan and assisted his social reform activities.\n\nGopalan worked as a doctor, chief surgeon, and [[Chief physician|superintendent]] at several hospitals in [[South India]], including in [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]], [[Tiruchirappalli|Tiruchirapalli]], [[Madurai]], [[Chennai]], [[Mysore]], and [[Bangalore]] ([[Bowring & Lady Curzon Hospitals]]). He returned to Kerala in 1896 and joined [[Kuthiravattam Mental Hospital|Calicut Lunatic asylum]] (now the Kuthiravattom Mental Hospital) as its first superintendent. Meanwhile, [[caste]] and [[racial discrimination]], evil practices, beliefs, and social injustices were prevalent in Kerala, and atrocities against women and children were at their peak. Gopalan extended his reform ideologies and propagated his reform activities by establishing Brahmo Samaj<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830 |last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Brahmo-Samaj|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net|title=brahmosamajnet|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net/history/history.html|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adaniel.tripod.com/brahmosamaj.htm|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> on 17&nbsp;January 1898 at [[Kozhikode|Calicut]]. To conduct Samaj meetings and prayers, a separate Brahmomandir (hall),(now the Ayathan Gopalan Memorial School<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ayathanschool.com/history.php|title=Ayathan school runs under the patronage of Brahmosamaj|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>), Calicut, was opened to the public on 17&nbsp;October 1900. The Brahmomandir was inaugurated by [[Zamorin of Calicut|Mana Vikraman Ettan Thampuran]], the Zamorin King<ref>{{Cite book|title=The zamorins of Calicut: from the earliest times down to A.D. 1806|last=Krishna Ayyar, K. V., 1894-|date=1999|publisher=Publication Division, University of Calicut|oclc=607834506}}</ref> of Calicut. The second branch of Brahmo Samaj was established at [[Alappuzha]] in 1924. A Brahmomandir was also constructed in 1928 at: Poonthoppu, Kommady, Alappuzha (now Grihalakshmi Gandhi Smaraka Seva Sangam) with the donation by a [[landlord]] ([[Jenmi]]) of Alleppey, named Mangalath Cochoumini Channar. Channar was once a strict follower of [[Narayana Guru|Sree Narayana Guru]], but was later influenced by the reform activities of Gopalan and Brahmo Samaj. His daughter, Mangalath Cochoumini Mandhakinibai, spearheaded the reform activities at Alappuzha Brahmosamaj and was married to Gopalan's third son, Devadath Ayathan. This was the first Brahmo wedding conducted at Alappuzha Brahmo Samaj, which ignited the custom of Misra Vivaham all over South Kerala.\n\n== Social reform activities ==\nIn the year 1900, Gopalan along with his wife Kallat Kausallyaammal initiated the [[Sugunavardhini Movement]] and extended his social reform activities. Through this movement, he worked to foster human values in children,attract children to do social activities, protect the rights of women, and provide free education to girls and marginalized sections of society, especially the [[Harijan]] communities in Kerala, that were then ill-treated by the higher castes, such as the [[Brahmin]]s and the [[Nair]]s. He established the Lady Chandhawarkar Elementary School intends to educate girls and the underprivileged section of society. Weekly meetings were conducted at his home, Santhi Ashram. Women, children, and people from all walks of life gathered there to share their sorrows with Gopalan and Kausallyaammal, who worked to address them. After the sad demise of Kallat Kausallyaammal, her daughter-in-law M.C. Mandhakinibai Devadath, took over the baton to unite women and the lower sections of the community to help them assert their social rights. It was Mandakinibai Devadath who first proposed The concept of \"women's organization\".\n\n[[Narayana Guru|Sree Narayana Guru]] arrived in Malabar during the time when Ayyathan Gopalan was going through a period of vigorous campaigns among the lower sections of Malabar for the upliftment of the underprivileged people and social reforms. After seeing the reform activities of Gopalan, he said,\"Everything's done here, I have nothing new to do\". Gopalan, though averse to idolatry and temple building, did not join with Guru. Sensing the social relevance of the [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam|Sree Narayana movement]], Ayyathan did not oppose it either. Gopalan realized that social reform was his way of life and did not take part in the national movement or agitations.Unlike the [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam|Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana (SNDP)]], which had been established by Narayana Guru<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sreenarayanaguru.in/|title=narayana guru|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; \u1e62\u0101j\u012b, K. N. (2002). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru: j\u012bvita\u1e43 kr\u0325tika\u1e37 dar\u015bana\u1e43. Tr\u032e\u015b\u015b\u016br: Kar\u0332ant\u0332 Buks: Distribution Cosmo Books. |year=|isbn=|oclc=52929384|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; B\u0101lakr\u0325i\u1e63h\u1e47an, P. K. (1969). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru (in Malayalam). Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative : Society Ltd. |oclc=31116295|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana, Guru; Nityachaitanya, Yati (2003). That alone, the core of wisdom: a commentary on \u0100tmopade\u015ba \u015batakam, the one hundred verses of self-instruction of Narayana Guru. New Delhi: D.K. Printworld. |year=|isbn=9788124602409|oclc=915135852|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru (1961). Souvenir to commemorate the 107th birthday of Sree Narayana Guru. Singapore: Sree Narayana Mission. |year=|isbn=|oclc=498088723|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; Kesavan Vaidyar, C. R (1990). \u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru Svantha\u1e43 Vachana\u1e45ga\u1e37iloode (in Malayalam). K\u014d\u1e6d\u1e6daya\u1e43: \u1e0ci. \u1e62i. Buks: Distributors, Current Books. |year=|isbn=|oclc=27111533|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A prophet of peace or Sree Narayana Gurudev of labor (a study).|last=Theerthan, Swami Dharma.|date=1933|publisher=The City Press|oclc=78599841}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Garland of visions : Dar\u015banam\u0101l\u0101 of Narayana Guru|last=Narayana Guru, 1856-1928.|date=2007|publisher=D.K. Printworld|isbn=978-8124603918|oclc=167576536}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Narayana Guru|doi = 10.1163/2212-5019_beh_com_9000000256}}</ref> and was influential around the same time, the [[Sugunavardhini Movement]] and Brahmo Samaj were composed mostly of professionals and intellectuals, including [[Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi|Brahmananda Swamisivayogi]], [[Vagbhatananda|Vagbhatananda Guru]], and Brahmavadi P. Kunhiraman, all with a more secular approach to reform.\n\nOther eminent personalities who worked with [[Brahmo Samaj]] and [[Sugunavardhini movement]] were: G. Subbha Rao, Kallingal Madathil Rarichan Mooppan, Kunjikoru Mooppan, C. Achuthan Vakeel, B.S.T. Mudaliyar, Rao Bahadur V. V. Govindan, Kallat Raghavan, Swami Aryabhadhan, Swami Brahmavradhan, Padmanabha Panikar, Sadhu Sivaprasad, Rama Sasthrikal, Manjeri Ramayyar, [[Mithavaadi Krishnan|Mithavadi C. Krishnan]], Lady Chandhawarkar, Rabindranath Tagore, Kesub Chandrasen, [[Rajnarayan Basu|Raj Narayan Basu]], [[Ramananda Chatterjee|Ramananda Chatterji]], Debjyothi Burman, Sasi Bhushan Basu, Satishchandra Chakraborthi, Jatheendrakumar Majumdar, and [[Mahadev Govind Ranade|Justice Ranade]].\n\nIn addition to uplifting the underprivileged and the marginalized, and educating women and [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|the underprivileged]], their movement led to several reforms, such as opposing idolatry, promoting and conducting Misra Vivaham (inter-caste marriages), Misra Bhojanam (inter-dining), spreading women's education, maintaining gender equality, eradicating un-touchability,caste and racial discrimination, conducting mass prayers and communion debates. Gopalan also took part in the Thali Road strike (Samaram at Calicut).\n\nThe hymns for prayers to be sung at Brahmosamaj were composed by Gopalan himself and compiled it in his book ''Keerthanaratnamala.'' He also conducted several inter-caste marriages at Brahmosamaj and worked to promote non-idol worship. \"[[Brahmo Dharma|Brahmodharma]]\" better known as the Brahmosamaj Bible, written in the [[Bengali language]] by [[Debendranath Tagore|Maharshi Debendranath Tagore]] were translated by him into Malayalam language. He promoted his reformist ideologies by conducting dramas, public awareness campaign, and through his writings.\n\nOn 4 June 1917, Gopalan was honored by the British Government with the highest civilian award and title, [[Rai Sahib|Rao Sahib]],<ref>\"British India: INDIAN TITLE BADGE (MYB # 327), RAO BAHADUR & RAO SAHIB MEDALS\". worldofcoins.eu. Retrieved 18 October 2014.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=rai sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=medal|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofcoins.eu/forum/index.php?topic=21524.0|title=rao sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Introduction to the Constitution of India By Sharma, Sharma B.k.. 2007. p. 83.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kaur, Madanjit (2008). Maharaja Ranjit Singh. |publisher=Unistar Books |year=|isbn=9788189899547|url-status=live}}</ref> for his social and humanitarian services.\n\nHe died on 2 May 1948, at the age of 87.\n\n==Works==\nGopalan translated the Bible of Brahmosamaj, [[Brahmo Dharma|Brahmodharma]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The offering. [Reprinted on the occasion of the centenary celebration of Maharshideva's initiation into the Brahma Dharma].|last=\u1e6ch\u0101kura, Debendran\u0101tha, 1817-1905.|date=c. 1943|oclc=910095}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=1 January 2008|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref> initially  written in the [[Bengali language]] by [[Debendranath Tagore|Maharshi Debendranath Tagore]], to Malayalam in 1910. He also wrote many songs and [[Kirtan|keerthanams]] to be sung during [[Brahmoism|Brahmosamaj prayer]] meetings. He propagated his reform ideologies through drama, public awareness, and his writings. ''Saranjiniparinayam'', ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama), and ''Plaguefarse'' were among his famous dramas performed by the [[Vaidyaratnam P. S. Warrier|Kottakkal P. S. Warrier]] Nadaka Sangam throughout Kerala for many years. His other literary contributions are listed below:\n\n* ''Brahmadharmam''\n* ''Saranjiniparinayam'' (musical drama)\n* ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama)\n* ''Plague Farse'' (drama)\n* ''Keerthanaratnamala''\n* ''Brahmamatham''\n* ''Rammohunroy (Harikatha)''\n* ''Madhaaikyam''\n* ''Madhavum Guruvum''\n* ''Madhavan''\n* ''Aaradhanayude Randu Padikal''\n* ''Brahma Madhavum Ithara Madhangalum''\n* ''Jaathi''\n* ''Vivaahageethangal''\n* ''Jai Britannia''\n* ''Yeshu Daivamayirunnuvo!''\n* ''British Bharana Mahathmyam''\n* ''Ente Ammayude Ormadaykk'' (biography of mother Kallat Chiruthammal)\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan  ''Malayalam Memoir'' (2013) edited by V.R.Govindhanunni published by Mathrubhumi books, Kozhikode\n* Kesava Menon. K. P. (1974). ''Samakaleenaraya Chila Keraleeyar''. Sahithya Pra. Co. s: Sahithya Pra. Co. s. p.&nbsp;239\n* Kausallya Gopalan (1932) Biography written by [[Vagbhatananda]] guru, published by Mathrubhumi Press, Calicut in 1932\n* ''Mughaparichayam'' (1959) Govindan A.C. Published by K.R.Brothers, Kozhikkode. p.&nbsp;155 p.&nbsp;156 p.&nbsp;157 p.&nbsp;158 p.&nbsp;159\n* ''Ente ammayude ormadaykk'' (1901) Biography of Kallat Chiruthammal, written by DR.Ayathan Gopalan.\n* Prof. Sreedharan Menon .A. (1967). ''A Survey of Kerala History''. Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative Society [Sales Dept.]; National Book Stall.\n* Prof.Sreedharamenon .A. (1987) ''Kerala History and its Makers'', Kottayam; National bookstall\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (1988), ''Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations'', Mittal Publications, {{ISBN|9788170990949}}\n* P. Govindapilla (2010) Kerala navothanam yuga sandhadikal yuga silpikal chintha pp\n* [[Vagbhatananda#CITEREFKurup1988|Kurup (1988)]], p.&nbsp;94\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". ''Social Scientist''. '''16''' (9): 35\u201345. {{doi|10.2307/3517171}}. {{JSTOR|3517171}}.\n* Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair ''Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku''(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )\n* ''Biography of Brahmananda Swami Sivayogy'' by A K Nair\n* ''Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi'' by Pavana\n*''Journal of Indian history'', University of Kerela Press, 2001 p270\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyathan Gopalan}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brahmoism]]\n[[Category:Indian medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Kerala]]\n[[Category:People from Thalassery]]\n[[Category:Reform movements]]\n[[Category:Social reformers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian physician, writer, social reformer and philanthropist}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Fanpov|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = RaoSahib\n| name               = Ayyathan Gopalan\n| image              = Appan.jpg\n| caption            = Darsarji\n| other_names        = Darsarji\n| birth_name         = Ayyathan Gopalan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1861|03|03}}\n| birth_place        = Thalassery, Chettamkunnu (Pulappadi Illam)\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1948|05|02|1861|03|03}}\n| death_place        = Calicut Shanthi Ashram\n| resting_place      = Santhi Gardens (Ayathan family cemetry, Calicut)\n| movement           = Sugunavardhini movement\n| spouse             = {{marriage |Kallat Kausallyaammal|1878|1930}}\n| children           = 5\n{{endplainlist}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Madras Medical College]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Doctor|professor|social reformer}}\n| known_for          = Physician, Writing, Philanthropy, Social reform in Kerala\n| notable_works      = Bhramodarma malayalam (Bible of bhramosamaj)\n\nSaranjiniparinayam and Susheeladukham (Musical dramas)\n| mother             = Kallat Chiruthammal\n| father             = Ayyathan Chandhan\n| relatives          = \n| awards             = [[Rai Sahib]]\n}}\n{{Reformation in Kerala}}\n\n'''Rao Sahib Ayyathan Gopalan''', Social reformer of Kerala popularly known as '''Darsarji''', \"doctor\", a.k.a \"RaoSahib\", was an Indian physician, writer, social reformer and philanthropist. He is known mainly as the founder of the [[Sugunavardhini movement]], leader and propagandist of [[Brahmo Samaj]] in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|date=1884|publisher=[[Funk & Wagnalls]]|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> He denounced idol worship and fought to end those social practices he thought were unethical, but prevalent, in Kerala. Among his followers were [[Brahmananda Sivayogi]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmananda swami Sivayogy by A K Nair|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi by Pavanan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair \"Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku\"(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and His Selected Works by P.V. Gopalakrishnan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sreyas.in/brahmananda-sivayogi|title=sivayogi|website=|date=29 April 2013|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kerala Navothanam - Oru Marxist Veekshanam - P. Govindappilla (Chintha Publishers, Thiruvananthapuram-695001)|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and his selected works|last=Gopalakrishnan, P. V.|date=2002|publisher=Kalpaz Publications|isbn=8178351013|oclc=52726748}}</ref> [[Vagbhatananda|Vaghbatananda]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (1988), Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations |publisher=Mittal Publications|year=|isbn=9788170990949|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherdschalet.com, retrieved 19 March 2014|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". |journal=Social Scientist|volume=16|issue=9|pages=35\u201345|year=1988|url-status=live|doi=10.2307/3517171|jstor=3517171|last1=Kurup|first1=K. K. N.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vagbhatananda-admavidya.com/|title=Vagbhatananda|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mahar\u1e63i V\u0101gba\u1e6d\u0101nanda Gurud\u0113var.|last=Brahmavrathan, Swami.|date=1971|oclc=978079481}}</ref> and Brahmavadhi P. Kunhiraman. Gopalan honored Karat Govinda Menon (Sivayogi) as \"[[Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi|Brahmananda Swami]]\" for writing a collection of poems on the request of Brahmosamajists called \"Brahmasankeerthanam\" and also for extending his social services through [[Brahmo Samaj|Brahmosamaj.]] The formation of [[Sugunavardhini movement]], and Brahmosamaj played a significant role in the [[Kerala reformation movement]].\n\n==Biography==\nGopalan was born into the [[Ayathan School|Ayyathan]] family of Pulappadi Illam (Aristocratic Thiyya family of Malabar) in Chettamkunnu, [[Thalassery]], (formerly Telicherry), [[Kerala]]. He was the first son of Ayyathan Chandhan and Kallat Chiruthammal. His youngest sister, Ayyathan Janakiammal,<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Modern Kerala, Studies in social and agrarian relations (1988). Modern Kerala:Studies in social and agrarian relations|publisher=by K.K.N.Kurup. mittal publications 1988: K.K.N.Kurup.|year=1988|isbn=|location=|page=86}}</ref> was the first female doctor in Malabar, Kerala.\n\nHe attended [[Government Brennen College, Thalassery|Brennen School]] and [[Mission school|Mission High School]] and later joined [[Madras Medical College]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Annual Report of the Madras Medical College. Session 1855-56( -1876-77).|last=Madras Medical College.|date=1856\u201377|oclc=562478204}}</ref> on 19&nbsp;September 1884.He resisted immorality and superstition at an early age.  He was reluctant to follow any caste differences or customs.  During his college days,reading about the social renaissance movements in many countries he got attracted to [[Ram Mohan RoyRoy|Raja Ram Mohan Roy's]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nazir|first=Parwez|date=2011|title=Raja Ram Mohan Roy: Social Reform and Empowerment of Women|journal=Journal of Exclusion Studies|volume=1|issue=2|pages=1|doi=10.5958/j.2231-4547.1.2.013|issn=2231-4547}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sati, a writeup of Raja Ram Mohan Roy about burning of widows alive|last=Rammohun Roy, Raja, 1772?-1833.|date=1996|publisher=B.R. Pub. Corp|isbn=8170188989|oclc=38110572}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=1 January 2008|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Men I have seen; personal reminiscences of seven great Bengalis.|last=\u015a\u0101str\u012b, \u015aiban\u0101tha, 1847-1919.|date=1948|publisher=Sadharan Brahmo Samaj|oclc=11057931}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Killingley|first=Dermot|chapter=Rammohun Roy and the Bengal Renaissance|date=27 June 2019|pages=36\u201353|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198790839|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198790839.003.0003|title=The Oxford History of Hinduism: Modern Hinduism}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Reflections on the Bengal renaissance : [papers read at a seminar, \"Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance\"]|last=Seminar on Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance (1976 : Rajshahi University)|date=1977|publisher=Institute of Bangladesh Studies, Rajshahi University|oclc=557887410}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|chapter=Rabindranath Tagore: His Life and Thought|date=24 February 2016|pages=1\u201317|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315554709|doi=10.4324/9781315554709-1|title=The Philosophy of Rabindranath Tagore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> Brahmo Samaj. He joined Brahmo Samaj and engaged in its social activities.  since then he was an active executive member of the General Committee of Calcutta Brahmo Samaj. He participated in the committee's annual conferences at various locations across India, along with Brahmo leaders such as [[Keshub Chandra Sen|Kesub Chandra Sen]], [[Debendranath Tagore]], Sivanath Sastri, [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[R. G. Bhandarkar]], and others. In 1888, he obtained a medical degree with honors and entered into [[Public service|government service]]. After that, he worked as a [[medic]] in several hospitals across South India and as a medical lecturer. He also served as a magistrate during the [[British rule]] in Malabar.\n\nGopalan married Kallat Kausallyaammal on 30&nbsp;December 1894. According to the rituals involved, this was the first Brahmo wedding. Ramakrishna Gobal Bhandhakar, a Brahmo leader and social reformer at that time, conducted the wedding at the Madras Brahmo Samaj. Several Brahmo leaders presided over the wedding. Kallat Kausallyaammal was a supporter of Gopalan and assisted his social reform activities.\n\nGopalan worked as a doctor, chief surgeon, and [[Chief physician|superintendent]] at several hospitals in [[South India]], including in [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]], [[Tiruchirappalli|Tiruchirapalli]], [[Madurai]], [[Chennai]], [[Mysore]], and [[Bangalore]] ([[Bowring & Lady Curzon Hospitals]]). He returned to Kerala in 1896 and joined [[Kuthiravattam Mental Hospital|Calicut Lunatic asylum]] (now the Kuthiravattom Mental Hospital) as its first superintendent. Meanwhile, [[caste]] and [[racial discrimination]], evil practices, beliefs, and social injustices were prevalent in Kerala, and atrocities against women and children were at their peak. Gopalan extended his reform ideologies and propagated his reform activities by establishing Brahmo Samaj<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830 |last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Brahmo-Samaj|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net|title=brahmosamajnet|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net/history/history.html|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adaniel.tripod.com/brahmosamaj.htm|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> on 17&nbsp;January 1898 at [[Kozhikode|Calicut]]. To conduct Samaj meetings and prayers, a separate Brahmomandir (hall),(now the Ayathan Gopalan Memorial School<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ayathanschool.com/history.php|title=Ayathan school runs under the patronage of Brahmosamaj|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>), Calicut, was opened to the public on 17&nbsp;October 1900. The Brahmomandir was inaugurated by [[Zamorin of Calicut|Mana Vikraman Ettan Thampuran]], the Zamorin King<ref>{{Cite book|title=The zamorins of Calicut: from the earliest times down to A.D. 1806|last=Krishna Ayyar, K. V., 1894-|date=1999|publisher=Publication Division, University of Calicut|oclc=607834506}}</ref> of Calicut. The second branch of Brahmo Samaj was established at [[Alappuzha]] in 1924. A Brahmomandir was also constructed in 1928 at: Poonthoppu, Kommady, Alappuzha (now Grihalakshmi Gandhi Smaraka Seva Sangam) with the donation by a [[landlord]] ([[Jenmi]]) of Alleppey, named Mangalath Cochoumini Channar. Channar was once a strict follower of [[Narayana Guru|Sree Narayana Guru]], but was later influenced by the reform activities of Gopalan and Brahmo Samaj. His daughter, Mangalath Cochoumini Mandhakinibai, spearheaded the reform activities at Alappuzha Brahmosamaj and was married to Gopalan's third son, Devadath Ayathan. This was the first Brahmo wedding conducted at Alappuzha Brahmo Samaj, which ignited the custom of Misra Vivaham all over South Kerala.\n\n== Social reform activities ==\nIn the year 1900, Gopalan along with his wife Kallat Kausallyaammal initiated the [[Sugunavardhini Movement]] and extended his social reform activities. Through this movement, he worked to foster human values in children,attract children to do social activities, protect the rights of women, and provide free education to girls and marginalized sections of society, especially the [[Harijan]] communities in Kerala, that were then ill-treated by the higher castes, such as the [[Brahmin]]s and the [[Nair]]s. He established the Lady Chandhawarkar Elementary School intends to educate girls and the underprivileged section of society. Weekly meetings were conducted at his home, Santhi Ashram. Women, children, and people from all walks of life gathered there to share their sorrows with Gopalan and Kausallyaammal, who worked to address them. After the sad demise of Kallat Kausallyaammal, her daughter-in-law M.C. Mandhakinibai Devadath, took over the baton to unite women and the lower sections of the community to help them assert their social rights. It was Mandakinibai Devadath who first proposed The concept of \"women's organization\".\n\n[[Narayana Guru|Sree Narayana Guru]] arrived in Malabar during the time when Ayyathan Gopalan was going through a period of vigorous campaigns among the lower sections of Malabar for the upliftment of the underprivileged people and social reforms. After seeing the reform activities of Gopalan, he said,\"Everything's done here, I have nothing new to do\". Gopalan, though averse to idolatry and temple building, did not join with Guru. Sensing the social relevance of the [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam|Sree Narayana movement]], Ayyathan did not oppose it either. Gopalan realized that social reform was his way of life and did not take part in the national movement or agitations.Unlike the [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam|Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana (SNDP)]], which had been established by Narayana Guru<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sreenarayanaguru.in/|title=narayana guru|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; \u1e62\u0101j\u012b, K. N. (2002). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru: j\u012bvita\u1e43 kr\u0325tika\u1e37 dar\u015bana\u1e43. Tr\u032e\u015b\u015b\u016br: Kar\u0332ant\u0332 Buks: Distribution Cosmo Books. |year=|isbn=|oclc=52929384|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; B\u0101lakr\u0325i\u1e63h\u1e47an, P. K. (1969). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru (in Malayalam). Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative : Society Ltd. |oclc=31116295|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana, Guru; Nityachaitanya, Yati (2003). That alone, the core of wisdom: a commentary on \u0100tmopade\u015ba \u015batakam, the one hundred verses of self-instruction of Narayana Guru. New Delhi: D.K. Printworld. |year=|isbn=9788124602409|oclc=915135852|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru (1961). Souvenir to commemorate the 107th birthday of Sree Narayana Guru. Singapore: Sree Narayana Mission. |year=|isbn=|oclc=498088723|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; Kesavan Vaidyar, C. R (1990). \u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru Svantha\u1e43 Vachana\u1e45ga\u1e37iloode (in Malayalam). K\u014d\u1e6d\u1e6daya\u1e43: \u1e0ci. \u1e62i. Buks: Distributors, Current Books. |year=|isbn=|oclc=27111533|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A prophet of peace or Sree Narayana Gurudev of labor (a study).|last=Theerthan, Swami Dharma.|date=1933|publisher=The City Press|oclc=78599841}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Garland of visions : Dar\u015banam\u0101l\u0101 of Narayana Guru|last=Narayana Guru, 1856-1928.|date=2007|publisher=D.K. Printworld|isbn=978-8124603918|oclc=167576536}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Narayana Guru|doi = 10.1163/2212-5019_beh_com_9000000256}}</ref> and was influential around the same time, the [[Sugunavardhini Movement]] and Brahmo Samaj were composed mostly of professionals and intellectuals, including [[Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi|Brahmananda Swamisivayogi]], [[Vagbhatananda|Vagbhatananda Guru]], and Brahmavadi P. Kunhiraman, all with a more secular approach to reform.\n\nOther eminent personalities who worked with [[Brahmo Samaj]] and [[Sugunavardhini movement]] were: G. Subbha Rao, Kallingal Madathil Rarichan Mooppan, Kunjikoru Mooppan, C. Achuthan Vakeel, B.S.T. Mudaliyar, Rao Bahadur V. V. Govindan, Kallat Raghavan, Swami Aryabhadhan, Swami Brahmavradhan, Padmanabha Panikar, Sadhu Sivaprasad, Rama Sasthrikal, Manjeri Ramayyar, [[Mithavaadi Krishnan|Mithavadi C. Krishnan]], Lady Chandhawarkar, Rabindranath Tagore, Kesub Chandrasen, [[Rajnarayan Basu|Raj Narayan Basu]], [[Ramananda Chatterjee|Ramananda Chatterji]], Debjyothi Burman, Sasi Bhushan Basu, Satishchandra Chakraborthi, Jatheendrakumar Majumdar, and [[Mahadev Govind Ranade|Justice Ranade]].\n\nIn addition to uplifting the underprivileged and the marginalized, and educating women and [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|the underprivileged]], their movement led to several reforms, such as opposing idolatry, promoting and conducting Misra Vivaham (inter-caste marriages), Misra Bhojanam (inter-dining), spreading women's education, maintaining gender equality, eradicating un-touchability,caste and racial discrimination, conducting mass prayers and communion debates. Gopalan also took part in the Thali Road strike (Samaram at Calicut).\n\nThe hymns for prayers to be sung at Brahmosamaj were composed by Gopalan himself and compiled it in his book ''Keerthanaratnamala.'' He also conducted several inter-caste marriages at Brahmosamaj and worked to promote non-idol worship. \"[[Brahmo Dharma|Brahmodharma]]\" better known as the Brahmosamaj Bible, written in the [[Bengali language]] by [[Debendranath Tagore|Maharshi Debendranath Tagore]] were translated by him into Malayalam language. He promoted his reformist ideologies by conducting dramas, public awareness campaign, and through his writings.\n\nOn 4 June 1917, Gopalan was honored by the British Government with the highest civilian award and title, [[Rai Sahib|Rao Sahib]],<ref>\"British India: INDIAN TITLE BADGE (MYB # 327), RAO BAHADUR & RAO SAHIB MEDALS\". worldofcoins.eu. Retrieved 18 October 2014.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=rai sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=medal|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofcoins.eu/forum/index.php?topic=21524.0|title=rao sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Introduction to the Constitution of India By Sharma, Sharma B.k.. 2007. p. 83.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kaur, Madanjit (2008). Maharaja Ranjit Singh. |publisher=Unistar Books |year=|isbn=9788189899547|url-status=live}}</ref> for his social and humanitarian services.\n\nHe died on 2 May 1948, at the age of 87.\n\n==Works==\nGopalan translated the Bible of Brahmosamaj, [[Brahmo Dharma|Brahmodharma]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The offering. [Reprinted on the occasion of the centenary celebration of Maharshideva's initiation into the Brahma Dharma].|last=\u1e6ch\u0101kura, Debendran\u0101tha, 1817-1905.|date=c. 1943|oclc=910095}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=1 January 2008|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref> initially  written in the [[Bengali language]] by [[Debendranath Tagore|Maharshi Debendranath Tagore]], to Malayalam in 1910. He also wrote many songs and [[Kirtan|keerthanams]] to be sung during [[Brahmoism|Brahmosamaj prayer]] meetings. He propagated his reform ideologies through drama, public awareness, and his writings. ''Saranjiniparinayam'', ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama), and ''Plaguefarse'' were among his famous dramas performed by the [[Vaidyaratnam P. S. Warrier|Kottakkal P. S. Warrier]] Nadaka Sangam throughout Kerala for many years. His other literary contributions are listed below:\n\n* ''Brahmadharmam''\n* ''Saranjiniparinayam'' (musical drama)\n* ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama)\n* ''Plague Farse'' (drama)\n* ''Keerthanaratnamala''\n* ''Brahmamatham''\n* ''Rammohunroy (Harikatha)''\n* ''Madhaaikyam''\n* ''Madhavum Guruvum''\n* ''Madhavan''\n* ''Aaradhanayude Randu Padikal''\n* ''Brahma Madhavum Ithara Madhangalum''\n* ''Jaathi''\n* ''Vivaahageethangal''\n* ''Jai Britannia''\n* ''Yeshu Daivamayirunnuvo!''\n* ''British Bharana Mahathmyam''\n* ''Ente Ammayude Ormadaykk'' (biography of mother Kallat Chiruthammal)\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan  ''Malayalam Memoir'' (2013) edited by V.R.Govindhanunni published by Mathrubhumi books, Kozhikode\n* Kesava Menon. K. P. (1974). ''Samakaleenaraya Chila Keraleeyar''. Sahithya Pra. Co. s: Sahithya Pra. Co. s. p.&nbsp;239\n* Kausallya Gopalan (1932) Biography written by [[Vagbhatananda]] guru, published by Mathrubhumi Press, Calicut in 1932\n* ''Mughaparichayam'' (1959) Govindan A.C. Published by K.R.Brothers, Kozhikkode. p.&nbsp;155 p.&nbsp;156 p.&nbsp;157 p.&nbsp;158 p.&nbsp;159\n* ''Ente ammayude ormadaykk'' (1901) Biography of Kallat Chiruthammal, written by DR.Ayathan Gopalan.\n* Prof. Sreedharan Menon .A. (1967). ''A Survey of Kerala History''. Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative Society [Sales Dept.]; National Book Stall.\n* Prof.Sreedharamenon .A. (1987) ''Kerala History and its Makers'', Kottayam; National bookstall\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (1988), ''Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations'', Mittal Publications, {{ISBN|9788170990949}}\n* P. Govindapilla (2010) Kerala navothanam yuga sandhadikal yuga silpikal chintha pp\n* [[Vagbhatananda#CITEREFKurup1988|Kurup (1988)]], p.&nbsp;94\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". ''Social Scientist''. '''16''' (9): 35\u201345. {{doi|10.2307/3517171}}. {{JSTOR|3517171}}.\n* Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair ''Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku''(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )\n* ''Biography of Brahmananda Swami Sivayogy'' by A K Nair\n* ''Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi'' by Pavana\n*''Journal of Indian history'', University of Kerela Press, 2001 p270\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyathan Gopalan}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brahmoism]]\n[[Category:Indian medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Kerala]]\n[[Category:People from Thalassery]]\n[[Category:Reform movements]]\n[[Category:Social reformers]]\n", "name_user": "Barnard, A. M.", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayyathan_Gopalan"}
